### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

core

### Description

`ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl` is a great implementation of handling all of the various kinds of `NotificationSource`, and so it is convenient to use, but it also schedules change detection, which is something that, in certain scenarios, we would like to handle ourselves.



### Proposed solution

Change `ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl` so that `notify` is basically implemented like this:
```typescript
public notify(source: NotificationSource) {
    this.setExternalDirtyFlags(source);
    if (this.shouldScheduleTick()) {
        this.scheduleTick();
    }
}
```
Where `setExternalDirtyFlags`, `shouldScheduleTick`, and `scheduleTick` would all be `protected` methods.
Additionally,  export `ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl` as a public symbol, so that it can be sub-classed by user implementations.

This would allow us, in tests (for example), to use our own scheduler while still getting the standard dirty flags set, so that we don't need to deal with rogue `setTimeout`s being started (which is a condition that our test framework will fail a test for).  It would also prevent any source of non-determinism in our tests from change detection running at a time other than when the test asked for it to run.

### Alternatives considered

One alternative I tried was re-implementing `ChangeDetectionSchedulerImpl` ourselves, but it depends on other parts of Angular that are also not exported.

Another option would be to use an InjectionToken to inject `scheduleCallbackWithRafRace` by default, and then the user could just supply an alternative implementation at that layer.

